Change: Fixed the "Dev account" switcher in the topbar staying visible for real, Keycloak-authenticated sessions instead of only in the unauthenticated mock-data state it was designed for.
Investigation: While live-debugging the user's "not seeing live data" report via the Claude in Chrome browser tools, found their dashboard genuinely was authenticated (network requests hit `/api/v1/me/authorization`, `/api/v1/reports/dashboard-summary`, etc., all 200s) as `master.test@mbam.local`, yet the topbar still showed the dev-only account-switcher dropdown, whose visibility is gated on `isDemoWorkspace()` (`workspace.masterAccount.id === "master-001"`, the static mock fixture's id). Traced why: `services/workspaceService.ts`'s real hydration path (`hydrateAuthorizationWorkspace` → `applyTeamAuthorization` → `updateCloudWorkspace({roles, teamMembers})`, then `hydrateCloudWorkspace` → `updateCloudWorkspace({masterAccount: {name, currency}, ...})`) never touches `masterAccount.id` — `updateCloudWorkspace` only ever merges `name`/`currency` into `masterAccount`, so the mock fixture's static id survives forever, even after fully real authentication. `data/mockWorkspace.ts` already exports `activateCloudWorkspace(user)` — a function that resets the workspace to an empty placeholder and correctly sets `masterAccount.id = user.id` (with its own passing unit test literally titled "removes demo data before rendering an authenticated account") — but it was never actually called anywhere outside its own test file. It was dead, unwired code.
Implementation: Called `activateCloudWorkspace(session.user)` at the top of `hydrateAuthorizationWorkspace()` in `mbam-web/src/services/workspaceService.ts`, right after confirming an online session exists and before `loadAuthorizationBootstrap()` runs. This clears the demo fixture and sets the real user id immediately; the subsequent `applyTeamAuthorization`/`updateCloudWorkspace` calls (already existing, unchanged) then populate the real team/business/product/transaction data on top of that correctly-id'd workspace, exactly as the existing test already asserted `activateCloudWorkspace` should behave.
Files changed: `mbam-web/src/services/workspaceService.ts`.
Verification: `npx tsc --noEmit` clean; `npm run lint` clean; `npm test` passed (21 files / 57 tests, unchanged, including the pre-existing `mockWorkspace.test.ts` that already asserted `activateCloudWorkspace`'s exact contract); live-verified via the Claude in Chrome browser tools against the user's actual running `npm run dev` session — reloaded `/dashboard/master` after the fix and confirmed via screenshot that the "Dev account" switcher no longer renders for the authenticated `master.test@mbam.local` session, while the rest of the topbar (Language, Ready to sync, Sign out) and the correct workspace name/role in the sidebar are unaffected.
Errors encountered: None.
Checks not run: `npm run build` not re-run for this specific change alone (already verified as part of the same session's polling changes minutes earlier with no intervening untested edits to build-affecting files); live-verified directly in the browser instead, which is a stronger signal for this particular UI-visibility fix than a build check would be.
Remaining risks: `activateCloudWorkspace` also runs on the offline-session path indirectly (any offline snapshot taken after this fix will have captured the correct `masterAccount.id`, since snapshots clone whatever `workspace` currently holds), but pre-existing offline snapshots saved before this fix (if any exist in a user's browser IndexedDB from earlier testing) would still carry the stale mock id until a fresh online sign-in re-saves the snapshot — not a functional problem (offline mode doesn't gate anything on `isDemoWorkspace()`), just noting it wouldn't retroactively fix already-saved snapshots.

FOLLOW-UP CORRECTION — 2026-07-03T11:39:27Z UTC: The credentials listed above do not work as browser sign-in passwords, and this was not caught before the change above shipped. Traced the actual runtime auth path after the user reported "default credentials not working even after db reset": `dev_demo_data.rs` (and the pre-existing `dev_seed.rs`) only write Postgres rows; the web app's sign-in screen (`AuthPage.tsx`) unconditionally redirects to Keycloak's hosted login (confirmed no legacy-login branch exists in that component — consistent with the in-app login/signup forms being confirmed-dead and removed in the repo-cleanup change below). The Keycloak realm import (`keycloak/mbam-realm.json`) creates zero human users and has `registrationAllowed: false`, so none of these emails exist in Keycloak at all; a Postgres reset cannot fix that, since the missing piece isn't in Postgres. Further, even after manually creating a matching Keycloak user and enabling `KEYCLOAK_ALLOW_EMAIL_LINKING`, sign-in would still fail with a role mismatch unless that Keycloak user is also assigned the correct realm role (`master_owner`/`business_admin`/`shop_manager`/`cashier`) — confirmed via `authentication/context.rs`'s `AuthorizationContext::new`, which requires Keycloak's asserted role set to resolve to exactly the same single baseline as the local membership grants, or the whole request fails closed with 401. Documented the full linking procedure (including the previously-missing role-assignment step) in `mbam-api/DEVELOPMENT_TEST_ACCOUNTS.md`. This gap is pre-existing (predates this session's demo-data work — it affects the original `dev_seed.rs` test accounts identically) and is a documentation/dev-experience gap, not a code defect requiring a fix in `dev_demo_data.rs` itself.

